</p>
<p>July</p>
<p>with the spy glass prevented us from dissovering the truth for some time.  Being still at a loss which way to steer we thought it best to stay here for the night.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Saturday 19<sup>th</sup></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Very cold this morning.  The men were sullen and silent and I must confess that I was not at my ease for no one would venture to say what course we ought to take lest he might be wrong and subject himself to the reproaches of the rest<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[A]</span>t last I desired the guide to follow the dictates of his own mind<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  He instantly mounted and directed his way along the banks of the Mississouri.  Some of the men looked gloomy and were not free of apprehension.  Saw some Buffaloes and the Carcass of one lately killed.  The brains were taken out <span class="AddHand-author">apparently</span> for the purpose of dressing leather<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>his Circumstance revived the drooping spirits of our party as it is well known that no war party would take the brains of an animal it must therefore have been done by some hunters and we flattered ourselves that these were Mandanes<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Saw several Cabries<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Crossed a small river<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Came to the top of an eminece &#8212; here our guide recognized our Situation and pointed out to us <span style="text-decoration:underline;">La lodge du Serpent</span> distant about four leagues to ESE.  This discover<span class="AddHand-author">y</span> recovered our good humour and thousands of questions were put to the poor guide before he could answer one.  In this manner we proceeded until noon.  Passed three small rivulets near which <span class="AddHand-author">were</span> several hills</p>
